You're on the right track, Gira! However, there seems to be a minor redundancy. You've wrapped `PaperProvider` twice - once around `<RootLayoutNav />` and then again inside it around `<Stack />` and `<InfoModal />`. There's no need for this double wrapping.

In your case, you should only wrap `PaperProvider` once at the highest level where all components are children of it directly or indirectly:

```jsx
export default function RootLayout() {
  const [loaded, error] = useFonts({
    SpaceMono: require('../../assets/fonts/SpaceMono-Regular.ttf'),
    ...FontAwesome.font,
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    if (error) throw error;
  }, [error]);

   return (
      <>
        {!loaded ? <SplashScreen /> :
          <PaperProvider theme={theme}>
            <RootLayoutNav />
          </PaperProvider>
        }
      </>
    );
}

function RootLayoutNav() {
  // All these will have access to paper’s context/theme as they are nested within PaperProvider in parent component.
  return (
     <>
       <Stack />
       <InfoModal />
     </>
   )
}
```

This way everything inside `RootLayoutNav`, including any other navigators/components that get added later on will have access to React Native Paper's functionality without changing any existing functionality.

